<HEAD>Assembly in Indian State Dissolved</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The central government on Friday dissolved the legislative assembly of opposition-ruled <LOCATION> Karnataka </LOCATION> state and put the state under federal rule, news reports said. Federal Home Minister <PERSON> Buta </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> told Parliament the move in the southern state came after the <ORGANIZATION> Janata </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dal </ORGANIZATION> party lost its majority, the reports said. By law, a new state assembly must be elected within a year. The Press Trust of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> news agency said <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>'s announcement was made amid protests from opposition members. <ORGANIZATION> Janata </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dal </ORGANIZATION>, headed by former Defense Minister V.P. <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, held 111 of the 222 seats in the house. It also was supported by seven independent members. <PERSON> Buta </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> said the party lost its majority after 19 legislators withdrew support. He said Gov. <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Venkatsubbiah </PERSON> reccomended dissolution of the assembly to President <PERSON> Ramaswamy </PERSON> <PERSON> Venkataraman </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> PTI </ORGANIZATION> quoted <LOCATION> Karnataka </LOCATION> Chief Minister S.R. <PERSON> Bommai </PERSON> as saying he had the support of 120 members in the house. <PERSON> Bommai </PERSON>, leader of the <ORGANIZATION> Janata </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dal </ORGANIZATION> party in the state, said wide opposition would arise if the assembly was dissolved, <ORGANIZATION> PTI </ORGANIZATION> reported from <LOCATION> Bangalore </LOCATION>, the capital of <LOCATION> Karnataka </LOCATION>. The federal government is led by Prime Minister <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>.
