<HEAD>Dissident Priest, Four Others Removed from Ballot in Moscow District</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The names of dissident priest <PERSON> Gleb </PERSON> <PERSON> Yakunin </PERSON> and four other announced candidates were removed Friday from a ballot for the new Soviet parliament, a colleague reported. <PERSON> Yakunin </PERSON>, a Russian Orthodox priest, and the four were blocked from the ballot in a central district in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> on grounds they did n't live or work in the district, said <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Popkov </PERSON>, a Christian activist who attended the district meeting at the <ORGANIZATION> ZIL </ORGANIZATION> car factory. Soviet election laws have no residency requirements. Many of those already elected to the new <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> Deputies were selected by organizations they did not belong to or from districts where they do not reside. <PERSON> Popkov </PERSON> said about 750 electors were at the district meeting, and he said they were picked `` in a crude move on the part of the top echelon'' of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. He said the head of the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> agreed to meet Saturday with <PERSON> Yakunin </PERSON> and the other rejected candidates to hear their complaints. None of the five was allowed to present his platform at the meeting and no election commission member was present to count the votes, <PERSON> Popkov </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. <PERSON> Yakunin </PERSON> was suspended from his religious duties for 20 years and imprisoned for dissident activities. After more than six years in prison and exile in <LOCATION> Siberia </LOCATION> he was released in March 1987 and assigned to a small parish near <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Popov </PERSON> said the four other rejected candidates were two writers, a criminal investigator and a military officer. The names of 11 candidates were placed on the district ballot.
