<SECOND>AM-Rejected Refugees,0276</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fifth Chartered Flight Departs South Padre Island For Central America</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BROWNSVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A group of 120 refugees was put on a jetliner and returned to <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> in the latest mass deportation of illegal aliens by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Immigration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naturalization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. The flight of the INS-chartered <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737 was the fifth such flight since Feb. 21, when the <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> began a crackdown on undocumented aliens crossing the <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Grande </LOCATION>. A previous charter flight of 231 aliens left <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> on March 13 and was believed to be the largest mass deportation by the INS. More than 1,300 Central Americans have been deported since the crackdown began. The refugees _ some smiling, other sulking _ were processed out of the <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> detention camp near <LOCATION> Bayview </LOCATION> and filed into four buses bound for the <LOCATION> Brownsville-South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Padre </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>. There were no Nicaraguans on the flight, although more than a quarter of the 1,250 detainees at the camp are from <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. Nicaraguans are the only nationality to have escaped the crackdown, thanks to a directive issued by then-Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, in July 1987. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> requested that the <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> encourage asylum applications and work authorizations for refugees fleeing the leftist Nicaraguan government. Deportation for Nicaraguans must be approved by <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> headquarters in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> D.C </ORGANIZATION>. Among the immigrants deported Thursday were 68 Salvadorans, 38 Guatemalans and 14 Hondurans. The <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> said 703 refugees applied for asylum in the <LOCATION> Harlingen </LOCATION> district since Feb. 21. Of those applicants, 72 Nicaraguans and six Salvadorans were granted asylum. The rest were detained to be sent back to their homelands.
</TEXT>
