<HEAD>Most North Carolina Boys Try Tobacco by Seventh Grade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASHEVILLE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than a third of the first-grade boys in rural <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> have tried smokeless tobacco, and the number increases to 70 percent by seventh-grade, a study shows. The recent <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carolina </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Asheville </LOCATION> study found that the most frequently stated reason for using smokeless tobacco was its taste, followed by peer pressure, a desire to feel `` grown up'' and the influence of role models such as athletes. The study used children in grades one, three, five and seven in urban and rural schools in western <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>. `` It was apparent during the administration of our questionnaire that the first-graders clearly understood what oral tobacco was,'' said <PERSON> Cheryl </PERSON> <PERSON> McClary </PERSON>, co-author of the study. `` In two of the rural schools, several little boys immediately jumped up to show their containers of chewing tobacco, which they kept in their back pocket.'' State law allows a 6-year-old to buy and use smokeless tobacco but prohibits the sale of cigarettes or cigarette papers to anyone under 17.
