<SECOND>PM-Skinner-Flight 103,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Victims' Relatives Still Want Probe; Skinner Goes to Europe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Relatives of Americans killed in the bombing of <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> Flight 103 say they are encouraged by recent government response to aviation security problems but still want a broad investigation into the incident. Transportation Secretary <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> on Friday announced rejection of calls for an independent commission to look into the Dec. 21 bombing. He then took off for <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> to meet with transportation officials in five countries, <PERSON> Bert </PERSON> <PERSON> Ammerman </PERSON>, spokesman for relatives of nearly 200 Americans killed in the explosion over <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, expressed disappointment with the decision, saying, `` We feel there's enough information that's been uncovered that only an independent investigation can deal with appropriately.'' <PERSON> Ammerman </PERSON>'s brother, <PERSON> Tom </PERSON>, was killed in the bombing. Among concerns of the relatives are the lack of a public warning of threats against the flight, security procedures that failed to detect the plastic explosive which authorities say was believed planted by terrorists, and inadequate government response after the incident. <PERSON> Ammerman </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Demarest </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, said, however, there have been several positive developments since the relatives staged a rally and met with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and other officials in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> on April 3, including steps to improve aviation security. He said the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> had agreed to escort relatives who want to visit <LOCATION> Lockerbie </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> was meeting in <LOCATION> Naples </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, this weekend with the administration's nominee to head the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, Adm. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Busey </PERSON>, who is <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> commander for <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, and next week with government and airline officials in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON>, in a news conference for foreign journalists covering <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, said he would push for security initiatives that would `` encourage international travelers to retain their justified confidence in the system's safety.'' <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> carriers have given `` unbelievable attention'' to security and are the safest in the world. His spokesman, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Prosperi </PERSON>, said <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> and other transportation and security officials were flying most of the way on a government plane to meet a tight schedule but would likely make at least part of the trip aboard commercial airliners. <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON>, in a letter to <PERSON> Ammerman </PERSON> rejecting the call for a separate investigation, said, `` For a variety of reasons, we do not believe formation of an independent commission is necessary or prudent.'' The letter was accompanied by a five-page outline of administration action since the Pan Am explosion. <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> said he had confidence in the investigation by Scottish and West German authorities and the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> and believed those responsible for planting the bomb, which investigators have said was hidden in a radio-cassette, will be apprehended and prosecuted. `` I can assure you that in my opinion the investigation is moving at full speed,'' <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> said. `` I think that eventually and hopefully in the not too distant future, the public will know the full story there.'' He said it was important not to disclose targets of the investigation or the information being sought. <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> said his trip would review screening given foreign nationals hired by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airlines abroad and seek diplomatic approval for installation of devices to detect plastic explosives in airports used by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> carriers abroad.
