<HEAD>Central Park after Dark: Safe or Scary?</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf, `Four teenagers ..., to UPDATE with further arrests,
doctor's statment that victim has a chance of full recovery.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The rape and beating of a jogger has reinforced the reputation of <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION> as a haven for criminals, which city officials say is an unfair stereotype of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s most famous urban park. `` Generally, crime in the park is low. It is safe to jog in Central Park,'' said police Chief of Detectives <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Colangelo </PERSON> after the Wednesday night attack by a marauding gang of teen-agers left a 28-year-old woman near death. `` There's danger in jogging anywhere,'' <PERSON> Colangelo </PERSON> said. `` But we do n't feel it's inordinately dangerous here.'' The park's reputation for illegal activity has been reinforced in recent years by several highly publicized incidents: <PERSON> Jennifer </PERSON> <PERSON> Levin </PERSON>'s 1986 strangling by `` preppie killer'' <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Chambers </PERSON>, a shooting a month earlier that left a police officer, <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> McDonald </PERSON>, paralyzed, and a 1983 free concert by <PERSON> Diana </PERSON> <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> that drew packs of thieves. The victim of the latest attack, an investment banker, remained unconscious on life-support systems Friday at <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>, said hospital spokeswoman Aura Retamoso. The woman lost roughly three-quarters of her body's blood in the attack, and suffered a fractured skull, severe head lacerations, brain contusions, fractured facial bones and bruises from head to toe in the assault by a dozen teens, said Dr. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kurtz </PERSON>, assistant chief of surgery at the hospital. <PERSON> Kurtz </PERSON> said that on Friday her pulse rate `` went way up'' when her mother spoke to her. `` So at some level she's processing information today which she was n't doing yesterday,'' he said. He said the next four days were crucial for her health, but added `` she has a fighting chance of making a full recovery.'' Seven teen-agers were arrested Friday and charged with attempted murder, rape and assault in the attack. Police said additional arrests were expected. <PERSON> Colangelo </PERSON> said the woman was attacked by some members of a group of 32 teens who went to the park Wednesday night to `` raise hell, attack joggers, steal bicycles.'' Within 10 minutes, they had assaulted three men, including a jogger and a homeless man. They later split up into three groups after spotting a police cruiser and terrorized at least nine people during a two-hour period. <PERSON> Colangelo </PERSON> said the youths told investigators the crime spree resulted from a pastime called `` wilding.'' `` It's not a term that we in the police had heard before,'' the chief said. `` They just said, ` We were going wilding.' In my mind at this point, it implies that they were going to go raise hell.'' `` Central Park is the focus of national attention. Every incident that happens there is news _ especially if it's grisly,'' Parks Commissioner <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Stern </PERSON> said Friday. Last year, police had reports of 51 assaults and 13 rapes in the park, compared with 71,030 assaults and 3,412 rapes citywide. Of last year's attacks in the park, a dozen involved joggers; in 1987, 13 joggers were assaulted in the park. The rape Wednesday was the third rape reported this year in Central Park, police said. Officials say the crime reports for the park are low for an area larger than the country of <LOCATION> Monaco </LOCATION>. On a busy day, hundreds of thousands of people pass through the park. Officials acknowledge the park has dangers after dark. `` It's safer to use it by day,'' <PERSON> Stern </PERSON> said. But he said, `` People should n't give up on the park any more than you would give up on air travel because of a plane crash.'' <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Lebow </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Road </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Runners </ORGANIZATION> club, tells evening joggers to avoid the northern area of the park, where the Wednesday attack occurred. That area, bordering on <LOCATION> Harlem </LOCATION>, has more rugged terrain and hiding places for criminals. <PERSON> Lebow </PERSON>'s warning is based on history: One of his group's members was raped in almost the same spot while jogging through the park five years ago. Mayor <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> also sounded a warning Friday about jogging: `` If you do it in some parts of this town, you're endangering your physical well-being, maybe occasionally even your life.
