<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Thousands Who Packed Square Demanding Democracy Depart</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with nine grafs to UPDATE with students leaving square
without incident after 15 hours of unrest, details. Picks up graf 7 pvs,
`Party general ...' EDITS to conform.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos BEJ6,10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than 100,000 students peacefully left <LOCATION> Tiananmen </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION> on Saturday after staging 15 hours of protests demanding democracy and an end to dictatorship in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. Student leaders decided to withdraw from the square at about 1:45 p.m. -LRB- 12:45 a.m. Saturday -RRB- after officials reopened the square to ordinary crowds that had swelled by the tens of thousands and become increasingly unruly. Earlier the students, raising their fists and chanting `` long live freedom,'' confronted the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> leadership as they filed into a memorial service for ousted party leader <PERSON> Hu </PERSON> <PERSON> Yaobang </PERSON> in the Great Hall of the People beside the square. The death of Hu, 73, from a heart attack last Saturday has sparked massive student protests. The students Saturday afternoon marched out of the square waving colored banners, calling for democracy and chanting `` arise citizens.'' Traffic was stopped along <LOCATION> Changan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Boulevard </LOCATION>, the capital's main avenue, and people climbed trees to get a better view of the procession. The students said they would go back to their campuses and begin a boycott. They shouted `` Down with dictatorship!'' again and again. Demonstrators filled a street dividing the square from the Great Hall, which was guarded by a triple line of <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> soldiers. Party General Secretary <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> <PERSON> Ziyang </PERSON>, <PERSON> Hu </PERSON>'s successor, delivered a 10-minute address at the memorial service. He said Hu `` worked unswervingly'' for the party and Marxist ideals during his 60-year revolutionary career, About 4,000 mourners, led by senior leader <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON> and members of the Politburo, attended the ceremonies. <PERSON> Hu </PERSON>'s body was draped in the red flag of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. Most of the mourners wore <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> jackets and trousers but <PERSON> Hu </PERSON> was dressed in a Western suit. <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> made no specific mention about <PERSON> Hu </PERSON>'s ouster, but said he was a man `` brave enough to admit his mistakes and to insist upon what he thought was right. He never tried to hold back his own opinions.'' <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> praised <PERSON> Hu </PERSON>'s `` unusual courage and resourcefulness'' in redressing the wrongs done to intellectuals and other citizens during the radicals' 1966-76 Cultural Revolution. <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON>, 84, walked around the casket and shook hands with <PERSON> Hu </PERSON>'s wife. The student rallies have filled Tiananman square since Monday and are much larger than pro-democracy demonstrations in the winter of 1986-87 that led to the ouster of Hu, an outspoken reformist. `` Long live democracy, long live freedom, down with bureaucracy, down with corruption!'' the students chanted as the officials entered the Great Hall. The students also yelled, `` Severely punish strong-armed tactics!'' a reference to purported police beatings of some students during a clash in front of the nearby <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> headquarters Thursday morning. Chinese observers said the overnight demonstration on the square was one of the largest of its kind ever since the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> victory over the Nationalists in 1949. Tens of thousands of students from about 30 universities, many bearing wreaths for <PERSON> Hu </PERSON> and pro-democracy banners, streamed into the square about Friday midnight, where up to 100,000 people had congregated during a day of rallies. The students gathered in circles centered around a wreath-laden monument to revolutionary heroes and sang, eulogized <PERSON> Hu </PERSON> and held debates about democracy. Some outspokenly criticized the Communist system. `` No one believes in Communism anymore,'' said one 34-year-old teacher. `` No one believes in the party. The party is strangling <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Ren </PERSON> <PERSON> Wanding </PERSON>, activist in the short-lived 1978 Democracy Wall period of relative tolerance for democratic views, told one audience of about 2,000: `` People are praying for the awakening of a legal system ... This is a historical necessity. Democracy Wall lives again!'' Others critized <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON> for holding onto power and demanded that Premier <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Peng </PERSON> resign, saying he lacked ability for the job. At about 6:15 a.m. Saturday, a student leader announced to cheers that the authorities agreed to let the students remain in the square while the party memorial service took place in the Great Hall. The <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> government on Friday announced that access to the Great Hall and the square would be restricted during the ceremony. Students feared police or soldiers would move in during the night to drive them out of the area. `` A victory for us. A big victory, the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> has backed down,'' said one jubilant student in the square. The students acknowledged, however, that authorities rejected a list of demands presented earlier in the week. They included more funding for education, public disclosure of the incomes of top leaders and an end to the ban on unauthorized demonstrations. Students said the most significant demand was for greater press freedom, a persistent theme during the demonstrations. The official press has given little coverage to the demonstrations except to report on alleged violent acts by demonstrators during Thursday's clash and issue warnings that those taking advantage of <PERSON> Hu </PERSON>'s death to promote anti-government activities will be punished. Tiananmen Square, a 100-acre plaza sided by the <LOCATION> Forbidden </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, the Great Hall and <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> <PERSON> Tse-tung </PERSON>'s mausoleum, is the symbolic center of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. Saturday's demonstration was the biggest since April 1976, when the death of Premier <PERSON> Chou </PERSON> <PERSON> En-lai </PERSON> sparked a huge outpouring of grief and anger toward the leftist government. That `` Tiananmen Incident'' set off events that were to lead to the overthrow of the leftists and the end of the 1966-76 Cultural Revolution. <PERSON> Hu </PERSON> was widely admired by students for his work in redressing the wrongs done to intellectuals during that decade of chaos. He was ousted as party leader in January 1987 after party conservatives accused him of being soft on student demonstrators and the trend toward `` bourgeois liberalization.'' On Saturday, one government worker in the demonstration said of <PERSON> Deng </PERSON>, `` Our leader is old. Maybe he is crazy. Many people hope he will die.'' <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> remains popular for his market-oriented reforms that have brought <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> some economic prosperity. But he has carried out only limited political reforms and does not tolerate opposition to one-party rule. <PERSON> Deng </PERSON>, who was believed at one point to have chosen <PERSON> Hu </PERSON> as his successor, approved <PERSON> Hu </PERSON>'s ouster after pro-democracy demonstrations rocked the nation in December 1986 and January 1987.
