<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An honor roll student searching for a way to protest his school's dress code found something his mother would think natty _ a bright red pair of her culottes. `` They're saying we ca n't wear shorts, but girls can wear skirts that are shorter than shorts, so they're indirectly discriminating against guys,'' said <PERSON> Aaron </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON>, who was sent home Thursday when he showed up in school sporting the outfit. On Friday, five other boys joined his protest by going to school in skirts. School officials told them to change their clothing or go home. Two went home, while the others changed to pants and went to class, said principal <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Blocker </PERSON>. The School Board's student dress policy clearly states that culottes _ sometimes referred to as `` split skirts'' _ are permissible. The policy does not say that only girls can wear culottes to school. `` Culottes are for girls,'' Blocker said. `` The handbook does n't say that, but that's what is meant It might be sex discrimination, but it's disruptive to the school.'' <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON>, a member of the baseball team and captain of the soccer team, said he feels `` more comfortable in shorts than in jeans. I never wear long pants unless I have to.'' `` The kids in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> are allowed to wear shorts to school,'' he said. `` I guess they're a bunch of illiterate dropouts because of it.'' <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> has scheduled a public hearing next week to consider changes to the student dress policy.
