<TEXT>
 Two farmers who claimed a neighbor's wandering bulls impregnated 32 of their heifers won a lawsuit, but got far less money than they sought to pay for abortions on the cows that were too young to have babies An <ORGANIZATION> Iowa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> jury awarded damages of $ 640 to <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> and <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Mieden </PERSON> on Thursday. The men had sued for $ 54,000. The $ 640, according to a veterinarian's testimony, would have covered the cost to administer abortion shots to the animals. The shots would have had no prolonged health effects. The trial pitting the Miedens against their neighbor, <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Vivian </PERSON>, began Monday. The Miedens claimed that in late June and early July 1986, two of <PERSON> Vivian </PERSON>'s bulls jumped a fence and bred with 32 of the 86 heifers that were in an adjacent pasture. The Miedens claimed that the heifers were too young to be bred, and that they lost milk production because of the early pregnancies. <PERSON> Vivian </PERSON> did not deny that his bulls were in the pasture with the heifers, but took the position that the Miedens could have done something to prevent damage to the heifers. He offered to have the heifers' pregnancies checked and to pay to have the pregnancies aborted. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Mieden </PERSON> said four of the heifers were aborted by a veterinarian, four aborted on their own and calves delivered by the other 24 heifers died. Two heifers died while giving birth, he said, and others suffered damaged reproductive tracts because they were too young to deliver.
