<HEAD>Communist Rebels Claim They Killed U.S. Colonel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Communist rebels today claimed responsibility for the ambush-slaying of a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> officer, and said it was in retaliation for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>' `` arrogant trampling'' of Philippine independence. Col. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> `` </PERSON> <PERSON> Nick </PERSON><PERSON> '' </PERSON> <PERSON> Rowe </PERSON>, a former <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> prisoner of war, was killed Friday by a shot to the head when gunmen in a stolen car sprayed his vehicle with bullets while he was on his way to work in suburban <LOCATION> Quezon </LOCATION>. The communist <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION> claimed responsibility in a statement delivered to news agencies. The letter bore the logo of the rebel army and was released on behalf of its chief, <PERSON> Romulo </PERSON> <PERSON> Kintanar </PERSON>. The statement threatened further attacks if the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> continues support of President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>'s fight against the 20-year Communist insurgency. `` The death of Col. <PERSON> Rowe </PERSON> signifies the firm commitment of the revolutionary forces to continue military actions against <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> personnel and installations as these are manifestations of the arrogant trampling of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> imperialists on the Filipino people's independence and sovereignty,'' the statement said <PERSON> Rowe </PERSON>, 51, was chief of the ground forces division of the <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> U.S.-Military </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, which provides training and logistical support to the <LOCATION> Philippine </LOCATION> military. <PERSON> Rowe </PERSON>, a native of <LOCATION> McAllen </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, was a decorated Vietnam War hero who was held in a cage for five years by the <ORGANIZATION> Viet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cong </ORGANIZATION> as a prisoner of war until he escaped in 1968. <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Platt </PERSON> called the killing a `` cowardly'' act. <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>, President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s press secretary, said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government will work with the <LOCATION> Philippine </LOCATION> government `` to track down and bring to justice those responsible for this assassination.'' Police said they recovered the assailants' car and traced it to a Filipino civilian who said it was stolen on April 7. Cartridges from bullets used in the killing littered the vehicle, police said. Police said up to three cars may have been used in the ambush, but witnesses said they saw only one carrying at least three men, a driver and two gunmen. One gunman had an M-16 rifle and the other a .45 - caliber pistol, police <PERSON> Rowe </PERSON>'s Filipino driver was wounded in the attack. It came five days after the communist <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> said the rebels were `` determined to make <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> imperialism pay dearly for the continuing stay of its bases and its escalating intervention in our people's affairs.'' The statement was issued to claim reponsibility for the bombing of a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> communications station in the northern province of Benguet on April 9. No one was hurt. In October 1987, rebels killed three Americans and a Filipino outside <LOCATION> Clark </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Air </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Base </LOCATION>, 50 miles north of <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>. Authorities then increased security at six <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military installations and civilian offices in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> today ordered additional security for the 1,000 sailors on the flagship USS Blue Ridge of the 7th Fleet. The ship arrived Friday for a four-day port call. Lt. <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Andrews </PERSON>, the fleet's spokesman, said the sailors were told, among other things, to travel in groups and stay away from dark alleys. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> deputy spokesman <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Boucher </PERSON> said Friday that a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> travel advisory issued March 15 `` indicates areas of the country where, because of criminal activity or terrorist activity, people should try to avoid.'' The advisory says most urban areas in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> including <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> are safe for travelers. <PERSON> Boucher </PERSON> indicated the advisory might be revised. `` I'm sure that will be looked at,'' he said. `` I would note that the threats that I have heard about were against official Americans, and were n't general threats to travelers.
