<HEAD>Attorney General: Mecham Can Run Again</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM F. RAWSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former Gov. <PERSON> Evan </PERSON> <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> can run for public office again despite the impeachment and conviction that ousted him a year ago, the attorney general said. `` Naturally ` I'm happy about it,'' said <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>, who has already announced a 1990 gubernatorial bid. `` It's what we thought it should be,'' he told television station <ORGANIZATION> KPNX </ORGANIZATION> from <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Neb </LOCATION>. The opinion issued Friday by Attorney General <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Corbin </PERSON> is nonbinding and could be challenged in court, but political leaders from both parties said they would n't challenge it. `` I think this issue should be settled by the voters of <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>,'' said <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> developer <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fife </PERSON> <PERSON> Symington </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, who has announced he will run against <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> in next year's <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> primary. <PERSON> Corbin </PERSON> said <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> was free to run becafice in the future. The impeachment and conviction did not disqualify <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> automatically, he said. His attorney, <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> MacPherson </PERSON>, said that <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> originally had intended to `` take this question of the ` Dracula clause' to the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> regardless of <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Corbin </PERSON>'s opinion.'' The Republican-controlled <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> ousted <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> on April 4, 1988, by more than the required two-thirds vote. But by a vote of 17-13 _ three short of a two-thirds majority _ the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> failed to invoke the so-called `` Dracula clause'' that would have driven a political stake through <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>'s heart and barred him from holding office again. Some legal scholars have said the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> might not have needed to vote on the clause because the state's constitution speaks of ouster and disqualification in the same sentence. And even if a separate vote was required, they said, a simple majority such as 17-13 might be enough. But in his 11-page opinion, <PERSON> Corbin </PERSON> said those who wrote the state's Constitution expected that there would be separate votes on ouster and disqualification. Political leaders from both parties welcomed the opinion and said it would be better to let <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> go ahead with his campaign for 1990. `` I think he ought to be able to run,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Usdane </PERSON>, a Republican who voted to oust <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> but also voted against the `` Dracula clause.'' `` I think it'd be better that he not be martyred,'' Usdane added. <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Minority Leader <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Stephens </PERSON>, a Democrat who also voted for impeachment and against the `` Dracula clause,'' said <PERSON> Corbin </PERSON>'s ruling `` is the right decision. Democratic Gov. <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> <PERSON> Mofford </PERSON>, who succeeded <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> following his ouster, said the attorney general's opinion would not change her plans to run for governor in 1990. <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> was elected on his fifth try for governor in 1986 and was impeached by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> after barely a year in office. The articles of impeachment charged <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> with concealing a developer's campaign loan, misusing state money and obstructing justice. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> convicted <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> on the misuse of funds and obstruction charges but deferred the obstruction charge to <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, where he was acquitted. <PERSON> MacPherson </PERSON> said <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> still plans to ask the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> next month to set aside the impeachment. `` We still have high hopes of either having the articles of impeachment dismissed, which would put Gov. <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> immediately back in office, or having a new trial declared,'' <PERSON> MacPherson </PERSON> said.
