<TEXT>
 Fears for a fragile bayou environment were receding after officials downgraded the estimated size of a spill of oil-tainted water to no more than 10,000 gallons. Meanwhile, the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> said an employee who was transferring the waste water from a barge when the spill occurred lacked proper certification. The spill of so-called `` slop water'' occurred early Friday on a loading dock on <LOCATION> Grand </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, about 35 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Baton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rouge </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Bobby </PERSON> <PERSON> Mayweather </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> GSX </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Land </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treatment </ORGANIZATION> in nearby White Castle. The barge was carrying 900,000 gallons of waste water from an Exxon plant in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>. It buckled in the middle while the waste was being unloaded into tanker trucks, <PERSON> Mayweather </PERSON> said. Authorities said the spill was quickly contained and that a cleanup would continue today. <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> had paid GSX to treat and dispose of the waste at White Castle, <PERSON> Mayweather </PERSON> said. Coast Guard Lt. Cmdr. <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> <PERSON> Kutz </PERSON> said one of the companies or an individual could be assessed civil penalties for conducting the transfer without proper documentation. Coast Guard Chief Warrant Officer <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Doss </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> GSX </ORGANIZATION> employee <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Vice </PERSON> did n't have the required <ORGANIZATION> Merchant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> certification for the job. <PERSON> Rick </PERSON> <PERSON> Davenport </PERSON>, facility manager for the GSX recovery unit in <LOCATION> Crowley </LOCATION>, confirmed that Vice was manning the operation when the spill occurred, but he declined to comment f