<HEAD>Foes of Racism Set March to Protest Neo-Nazi Skinhead Conference</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: March starts at 2 p.m. EDT.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN K. WILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COEUR D'ALENE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Demonstrators gathered today to protest a nearby white supremacist conference, but many people who oppose racism stayed away out of fear of violence. Law enforcement officers, meanwhile, made plans to head off any potential confrontations between the two groups. As many as 2,000 demonstrators were expected to march in the seven-mile `` Walk for Racial Equality,'' which is planned to end two miles from the Aryan Nations compound, site of the conference of neo-Nazi youths. Sheriff's deputies and officers from the <ORGANIZATION> Idaho </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Coeur </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> d'Alene </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> planned a show of force around the anti-racism marchers to discourage confrontations. `` We've established what we feel to be tactics that are going to ensure the safety of all the parties involved,'' said Capt. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Dickson </PERSON>. Fewer than 100 neo-Nazi youths were believed to be staying at the 30-acre ranch of <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Butler </PERSON>, founder of the <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jesus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christ </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Aryan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, a white supremacist organization that wants to turn the Northwest into a `` whites only'' homeland. <PERSON> Butler </PERSON> said white supremacist leaders, including <ORGANIZATION> Ku </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Klux </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Klan </ORGANIZATION> officials, will speak and conduct workshops. Sheriff's deputies set up checkpoints Friday on roads leading to the camp a few miles north of <ORGANIZATION> Coeur </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> d'Alene </ORGANIZATION> to check identifications of people entering the area. <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, organizer of <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nonviolent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Against </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Racism </ORGANIZATION>, the Coeur d'Alene-based group sponsoring the march, said she expected few problems. Although the march has been endorsed by the Rev. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Rainbow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION>, The New Jewish Agenda and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> Gov <PERSON> Booth </PERSON> <PERSON> Gardner </PERSON>, groups such as the Anti-Defamation League of B'Nai B'rith were staying away. <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Stern </PERSON>, regional <ORGANIZATION> ADL </ORGANIZATION> director in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, said his group was concerned about placing an additional burden on law enforcement and a potential for violence. <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Cecil </PERSON> <PERSON> Andrus </PERSON> also refused to endorse the march, saying it could promote violence and give the neo-Nazis more publicity. In a statement issued Friday, <PERSON> Andrus </PERSON> lashed out at the skinheads. `` The people of <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> stand united against hate groups and those who would spread a message of fear and intolerance,'' he said. Leaders of organizations formed during the past decade to combat the Aryan Nations planned a picnic and other events a few miles away from the white supremacist gathering. `` We think that a march just does them too much honor and respect,'' said <PERSON> Norm </PERSON> <PERSON> Gissell </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Kootenai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Task </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> on Human Relations.
