<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The man identified as the principal suspect in a dozen drug-related torture slayings in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> near the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> border denied he was the killer but said he may have information on the deaths, officials said. <PERSON> Hector </PERSON> <PERSON> Fragoso </PERSON> <PERSON> Burgueno </PERSON>, 45, was held without bond Friday at the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Correctional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> after his arrest late Thursday at a mobile home in an isolated area about 30 miles west of <LOCATION> Tucson </LOCATION>. `` He's the principal one, according to the witnesses,'' said <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Cecena </PERSON>, zone commander with the <ORGANIZATION> Judicial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> of the Mexican state of <LOCATION> Sonora </LOCATION>. Mexican federal and state authorities will file formal requests for <PERSON> Fragoso </PERSON>'s return to <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, officials said. <PERSON> Gerard </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> special agent, said <PERSON> Fragoso </PERSON> `` has made statements extricating himself from any culpability in the murders in <LOCATION> Agua </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Prieta </LOCATION>. However, he has said that he may be able to provide information that authorities are not aware of.'' <PERSON> Fragoso </PERSON> was found with a woman identified as his wife, <PERSON> Anna </PERSON> <PERSON> Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Fragoso </PERSON>. <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Coffin </PERSON>, deputy chief agent for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Border </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Patrol </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Tucson </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Fragoso </PERSON> was being held as an illegal alien under a federal immigration arrest warrant. His wife could be voluntarily deported to <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, officials said. <PERSON> Fragoso </PERSON> owned the ranch near the Mexican border town of <LOCATION> Agua </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Prieta </LOCATION> where the bodies were found on March 29 and April 1. He had shaved his moustache, changed his hair style and altered his eyebrows, but `` it did n't help him. We recognized him right away,'' said <LOCATION> Pima </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sheriff </LOCATION>'s Maj. <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON>. <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> said investigators found <PERSON> Fragoso </PERSON> after getting various tips, including some from a local crime hotline and from the TV show `` <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s Most Wanted,'' which had a segment Sunday on <PERSON> Fragoso </PERSON>. Authorities were investigating whether the <LOCATION> Agua </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Prieta </LOCATION> killings were linked to the slayings of five people whose bodies were found in a <LOCATION> Tucson </LOCATION> shed shortly before the <ORGANIZATION> Agua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prieta </ORGANIZATION> bodies were discovered. <PERSON> Cecena </PERSON> said 11 of the <ORGANIZATION> Agua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prieta </ORGANIZATION> victims apparently were killed after they witnessed the murder of one person. The <ORGANIZATION> Border </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Patrol </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Fragoso </PERSON> has an extensive arrest history, ranging from drug and weapons violations to assault, sexual assault and robbery. Like the unrelated ritual slayings of 15 people in <LOCATION> Matamoros </LOCATION> discovered last week, authorities consider the <ORGANIZATION> Agua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prieta </ORGANIZATION> killings to be drug-related.
