<HEAD>Syrians Fire Rockets At Christian Port</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Syrian forces today fired rockets into the port of <LOCATION> Jounieh </LOCATION>, the only escape route for <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s beleaguered Christians No casualties were reported as sporadic 122mm Soviet-designed Grad rockets exploded around <LOCATION> Jounieh </LOCATION>, 10 miles north of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, and the coastal highway running north to the ancient port of <LOCATION> Byblos </LOCATION>. The attack came during a three-day lull in the battle between the Syrians and allied Moslem Druse militia and the mainly Christian units of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s fractured armed forces under army commander Gen. <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>. By police count, at least 270 people have been killed and nearly 1,000 wounded in ferocious artillery, rocket and tank exchanges that began March 8 in the divided capital. Police, speaking on condition of anonymity, reported that an estimated 4,000 Christians were gathered at <LOCATION> Jounieh </LOCATION> to await ferries from <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>, 130 miles to the northeast, to take them to safety. The 4,000-ton <PERSON> Baroness </PERSON> <PERSON> M </PERSON>, one of two ferries that have carried 12,000 Christians to <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> in the last six weeks, was anchored off <LOCATION> Jounieh </LOCATION> on Friday night. It took 1,200 people from <LOCATION> Jounieh </LOCATION> in small boats. The other ferry, the <LOCATION> Larnaca </LOCATION> Rose, suspended its <LOCATION> Jounieh </LOCATION> run three days ago after it came under Syrian shelling near the lebanese port. Cypriot shipping officials said it was not known when the next ferry will sail for <LOCATION> Jounieh </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s Moslem-controlled Voice of the Nation today termed the Syrian rocketing a warning to ships to stay away from the besieged enclave. `` It will persist as long as the blockade imposed by <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> perists,'' it said. The latest fighting broke out two days after <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>, seeking to restore state authority, blockaded illegal ports south of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> run by Moslem militias. <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s troops in the 310-square-mile Christian enclave, which is ringed on the three landward sides by hostile forces, have not returned the Syrian fire since most fighting died down late Wednesday.
