<HEAD>Suspect Charged With Seven Murders; Will Return For Plea</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs to raise reference to automatic teller machines
and tighten; PICKS UP 18th graf pvs, `After his ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA ROSA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Automatic teller machines helped police track down a winery worker accused of murdering seven people, including his wife and two daughters. The <LOCATION> Sonoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> sheriff's office persuaded <ORGANIZATION> Wells </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fargo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> to extend unlimited credit to <PERSON> Ramon </PERSON> <PERSON> Salcido </PERSON> and arranged to track him through any transactions made with his automatic teller card, said Sheriff <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Michaelsen </PERSON>. A tip from <PERSON> Salcido </PERSON>'s sister and brother-in-law in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> also helped authorities find him, the <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Francisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chronicle </ORGANIZATION> reported today, citing unidentified <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> diplomatic and law enforcement sources. <PERSON> Salcido </PERSON>, 28, who also is accused of killing his mother-in-law and her two daughters and a co-worker at the winery where he was a forklift operator, was arraigned on murder charges Friday after being captured in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Salcido </PERSON> was reported to have run out of bank funds last week while on a cocaine-and-alcohol binge that friends said preceded the April 14 slaughter. He tried to use a bank card at least once at a <LOCATION> Wells </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Fargo </LOCATION> branch that morning in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rafael </LOCATION>, 30 miles south, and possibly again later in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> while heading for <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, authorities said. The manhunt ended Wednesday when <PERSON> Salcido </PERSON> was arrested in western <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> near his hometown of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mochis </LOCATION>. A spokesman for the sheriff's department, citing a gag order imposed by a judge on Friday, would not comment on the report about family members tipping off police. <PERSON> Salcido </PERSON>, who also is charged with three counts of attempted murder, appeared in court Friday in handcuffs and a bulletproof vest. He did not enter a plea but will return to court May 5. He could get the death penalty if convicted. <PERSON> Salcido </PERSON>'s attorney, Chief Public Defender <PERSON> Marteen </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said he expected <PERSON> Salcido </PERSON> would enter a plea of innocent by reason of insanity. He added that he would have his client undergo psychiatric and neurological tests. `` I expect to find some brain lesion or tumor,'' said <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, who called the crimes, `` so bizarre, so incomprehensible.'' `` God, I hope I find something,'' said <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, who also planned to ask that the trial be moved because of all the publicity the case has received. The prosecutor, however, discounted speculation that the rampage was fueled in part by alcohol and cocaine us and said he believed <PERSON> Salcido </PERSON> is legally sane. `` The final decision about his state of mind will be made in court,'' said District Attorney <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> Tunney </PERSON>. `` Those were not the acts of an irrational berserker.'' After his arrest, <PERSON> Salcido </PERSON> told Mexican television reporters and law enforcement agents he killed his American-born wife, <PERSON> Angela </PERSON>, 24, and a winery co-worker, <PERSON> Tracy </PERSON> <PERSON> Toovey </PERSON>, in a jealous rage, believing <PERSON> Toovey </PERSON> and his wife were romantically involved, according to federal officials. Also killed in the series of attacks across the <LOCATION> Sonoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> 40 miles north of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> were <PERSON> Salcido </PERSON>'s mother-in-law and his two sisters-in-law, 8 and 12. <PERSON> Salcido </PERSON> also is accused of killing two daughters, 1 and 4, who were found dead at a dump April 15. Their throats had been slashed. Another daughter, <PERSON> Carmina </PERSON>, who turns 3 on Monday, also was found at the dump with a slashed throat but is recovering and has identified her father as her attacker, police said.
