<TEXT>
 Suspected communist guerrillas attacked the homes of two government militiamen in the southern <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> today. Seven people, including three children and one militiaman, were killed, police said. A police report said the attack, with automatic rifles and grenade launchers, occurred in the remote town of <LOCATION> Sindangan </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Zamboanga </LOCATION> <LOCATION> del </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Norte </LOCATION> province, 40 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Pagadian </LOCATION> and 460 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>. Sgt. <PERSON> Gideon </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodrigo </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Sindangan </LOCATION> police station commander, said about 30 members of the communist <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> fired simultaneously on the two houses with M-16 rifles and M-203 grenade launchers. Seven occupants were killed and five were wounded, including the militiaman who survived, he said. <PERSON> Rodrigo </PERSON> said government militiamen owned the homes and that the attack was in retaliation for their participation in the government's campaign against the rebels. The insurgents took away the militiamen's farm animals, he said. In nearby <LOCATION> Zamboanga </LOCATION> <LOCATION> del </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sur </LOCATION> province, two militiamen were killed Friday when about 200 rebels attacked the town of <LOCATION> Mahayag </LOCATION> and held residents for nearly one hour before escaping, a military report said. It said the rebels issued a challenge to soldiers in the area and fought with them for 30 minutes. In another attack Friday, rebels killed two militiamen in the town of <LOCATION> Molave </LOCATION> in adjoining <LOCATION> Misamis </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Oriental </LOCATION> province, the military said.
