<HEAD>Walesa Says Solidarity Destined to Shrink</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Solidarity leader <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said today that the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc's first independent trade union probably will get smaller as other independent groups form in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. `` From Solidarity, other economic and political organizations will be born,'' <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said at a news conference ending his three-day visit to <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. `` Solidarity for the moment is huge but it will become smaller with the growth of other organizations. This is the logical course of events.'' The Polish independent trade union was crushed by security forces in 1981 and outlawed in 1982. <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s communist government restored the legality of Solidarity on Monday after reaching agreement with the Solidarity-led opposition on political and social reforms. The government is seeking support from Solidarity and aid from the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> to restore its shattered economy. Coinciding with the official recognition of Solidarity, President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> announced a $ 1 billion economic aid program for <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said the program was `` a great step forward taken by Mr. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>.'' <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, winner of the 1983 Nobel Peace Prize, indicated he planned to visit other countries as an `` ambassador of Solidarity'' but did not say which ones. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> came to <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> seeking economic investment in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and the blessing of fellow Pole Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> for the country's new political course. The Solidarity leader said he would like to see the pope make another trip to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> but that <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> had many obligations. `` And because we love him, we will spare him,'' <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said. `` For this reason, we told him not to worry so much about <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> _ we have reached these accords, worry yourself less. It's clear, though, that he wo n't listen to us and will continue to be concerned.''
