Any significant retreat from <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> will have to attract the court's three most junior justices _ <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>, <PERSON> Antonin </PERSON> <PERSON> Scalia </PERSON> and <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>. All are appointees of former president <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, an outspoken critic of the high court's abortion rulings. <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> criticized the rationale of <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> while dissenting from a 1986 decision striking down certain abortion regulations in <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>. But it is unknown whether she disagrees with the core holding of the 1973 decision _ that women have a fundamental right to abortion. <PERSON> Scalia </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> have not yet ruled in any abortion case, but many believe both favor cutting back abortion rights. `` Justice <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> is the key,'' <ORGANIZATION> NARAL </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Michelman </PERSON> said. `` We wrote our -LRB- friend-of-the-court -RRB- brief to speak to <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>.'' <PERSON> Dawn </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnsen </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> NARAL </ORGANIZATION> legal director who wrote the brief, said, `` If we are going to win it's likely to be by one vote. That's not the kind of victory with which one can be comfortable.'' In all, the justices received a record 78 friend-of-the-court briefs _ the judicial branch's equivalent of lobbying _ from interested individuals and organizations not actually involved of the <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> dispute. The justices often give such unsolicited advice close attention. The same can not be said, however, for the tens of thousands of letters and hundreds of telephone calls the court is receiving daily from Americans expressing their views on abortion. `` This is not a popularity contest,'' court spokeswoman <PERSON> Toni </PERSON> <PERSON> House </PERSON> said. `` This is a war of ideas, not numbers.'' If a war, it is one with no end in sight.
