<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here, at a glance, are the views of each <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> member on the court's 1973 <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> decision, reached by a 7-2 vote, that women have a constitutional right to abortion.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>SUPPORTERS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 _ Justice <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON>, 80 He authored the landmark <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> opinion and is its most impassioned champion on the court. He told a law school audience last fall the court might reverse the 1973 ruling this term. `` You can count the votes,'' he said. _ Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>, 82 A Roman Catholic, he reportedly steered the court's closed-door deliberations that led to the 1973 ruling and joined in <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON>'s majority opinion. _ Justice <PERSON> Thurgood </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON>, 80 He is the third remaining member of the <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> majority. _ Justice <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>, 68 Since joining the court in 1975, he consistently has voted to uphold the abortion right.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>OPPONENTS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 _ Chief Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rehnquist </PERSON>, 64 He was a dissenter in 1973 and, in subsequent abortion rulings, has voted to give states far greater authority to regulate abortions. _ Justice <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>, 71 The second dissenter from <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON>, he said in a subsequent abortion opinion that the 1973 decision `` essentially created something out of nothing.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>SWING VOTES</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 _ Justice <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>, 58 In a dissenting vote in 1986, she favored giving states more authority in regulating abortions and criticized the legal approach taken by <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON> in 1973. But she has never said that women do not have a constitutional right to abortion. _ Justice <PERSON> Antonin </PERSON> <PERSON> Scalia </PERSON>, 52 He never participated in an abortion case as a federal appeals court judge, and since joining the high court in 1986 has taken no public stand on abortion. _ Justice <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, 52 Although a federal appeals court judge for 12 years before joining the court last year, he never has ruled in an abortion case nor has he stated his views publicly on the issue.
