<HEAD>Congress Off to Rocky Start in Bicentennial Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The historic 101st <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is out of sorts. The institution began its bicentennial year pledging to cooperate with a new president and touting an ambitious legislative agenda. But lawmakers have spent their first four months killing a 50-percent pay raise in embarrassment, flinging morals charges at defense secretary nominee <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Tower </PERSON> and investigating the ethics of their highest-ranking official, <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>. `` This is worse than the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>,'' said Rep. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> McCurdy </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Okla </LOCATION>., likening the institution to the television tribunal `` The pay raise, <ORGANIZATION> John </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tower </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> _ I'm baffled. What's going on? I do n't think any incumbent comes out looking very good after this sideshow.'' By the end of last week, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> had met seven fewer days this year than it had by the same date in 1987, the beginning of the 100th <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. Sixteen laws have been enacted this year, none of them major and 10 of them commemorative measures like `` National Agriculture Day.'' Beyond the statistics, there's a widespread sense that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has been sleepwalking through its legislative paces this year, distracted and preoccupied by its own internal problems. `` We're tired of a do-nothing <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Okla </LOCATION>., as <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Republicans last week accused majority Democrats of ignoring important legislation `` We demand that the Democrats bring these issues before the House ... so we can do the job we were elected to do.'' The implication is that <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> and his top lieutenants are so busy playing defense against the 69 rules violations alleged against the speaker that they have lost their legislative compass. Democratic leaders, who are responsible for the Capitol's output, disagree and point to bipartisan agreements with the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration on the budget and aid to the Nicaraguan Contra rebels, and to legislation on the minimum wage, savings and loans, and military base closings `` While everybody would like to see the -LRB- <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> -RRB- matter resolved as quickly as possible, the function of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> is proceeding,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>, D-Wash., the majority leader `` The speaker is moving important legislative matters. It's not true that the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Representatives </ORGANIZATION> is in a gridlock condition.'' Congresses are notoriously slow-starting, especially in the first session of a two-year term. And <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> leaders did bide their time for the early part of the year waiting for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration budget proposals, appointments and legislative initiatives. Even at that, the year so far has been less productive than most. While the budget agreement does add some oil to the legislative machinery, it failed to seriously address the nation's deficit problem. And the base closings action was merely a ratification of steps taken last year by an independent commission that took the political heat off <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. `` It is a confluence of what would be the normal slowness, added to by some distractions,'' said <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Deering </PERSON>, a political scientist at <ORGANIZATION> George </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and close observer of the legislative process. `` That has conspired to make this, in appearance especially, a slow start. Instead of substance, they've had to focus on sidelights. The most blinding current sidelight is the <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> investigation. Last week, the ethics committee formally charged the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Democrat with 69 instances of violating House rules. Lawyers for <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> and the committee are fencing over arrangements for the speaker to appear and mount a personal defense before the panel, and it appears the case will drag on for at least a few more weeks. One aspect of the case, a complicated oil well transaction which yielded <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> huge profits last year, remains under investigation and could yet cause additional problems for the speaker. Waiting in the wings is a separate ethics case against <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, alleging that he improperly disclosed a covert <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> operation in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. Republicans say they plan to press the matter. `` He's shark bait right now, and that's not fun,'' said <PERSON> McCurdy </PERSON>. `` This is a crazy process.'' On the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> floor and in corners all around the Capitol, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> has replaced Tower and the pay raise as the prime topic of conversation. `` They're talking about it every second,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Beryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ark </LOCATION>. Even Democratic senators worried about their party's image have taken a rare interest in what happens on the other side of the building. One House Democrat, Rep. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, said the mood of his colleagues is at its lowest ebb in years. `` There's been a slowdown and a morale loss,'' <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON> said. `` It's a very bleak period. I've been in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> seven years and I've never felt so bad and down about being a member of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>.'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s defenders call the charges _ that he failed to report $ 145,000 in improper gifts from a friend with a direct interest in legislation, and sought to evade limits on outside income through bulk sales of a book he wrote _ trivial and the reaction to them overblown. `` It should be beneath the dignity of this House to question that kind of thing,'' said Rep. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Scheuer </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION> `` There is a certain sense of outrage that this process has taken on a life of its own that was never intended.'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> himself has sought to maintain a normal schedule, but with varying results. Much of his days lately have been consumed by meetings with his lawyer, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Oldaker </PERSON>, and with political allies plotting defense strategy. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s normally daily press conferences have become less frequent. At one recent one at which reporters peppered him with ethics questions, he finally asked in exasperation: `` Do you have any questions about the government of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>?''
