<HEAD>Black Voters Wonder How Long They'll Remain on the Sidelines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>'s march to City Hall by defeating two blacks has left the black vote in disarray and has many wondering whether <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>'s inauguration Monday will be his first and only or the first of many. <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>, son of the last of the big-city bosses, ended blacks' six-year grip on the mayoralty by soundly beating acting Mayor <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> in February's Democratic primary and by doing the same to <PERSON> Alderman </PERSON> <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> six weeks later <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> will complete the last two years of the second term of the city's first black mayor, <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON>, who died in 1987. <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>'s father, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>, won six consecutive terms. Whether the younger <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> is in for the long term may depend less on his own actions than on whether black voters can regroup after splintering between <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> and <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>. `` We knew what the stakes were this time around and we let it get away from us once. ... So I'm taking a dismal view of things for the future,'' said <PERSON> Lu </PERSON> <PERSON> Palmer </PERSON>, an influential black radio commentator and political activist, `` I do n't see any possibility of winning the mayor's office back by 1991, and let's face it, if <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> gets a foothold then,'' he said, `` the office is probably his until the year 2000-and-something.'' Most election post-mortems have centered on the low black turnout that crippled both <PERSON> Sawyer </PERSON> and <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, despite the efforts of former Democratic presidential candidate <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> on behalf of both. The ensuing debate among blacks has centered on whether they should spend their time on the sidelines developing a black independent party, as <PERSON> Palmer </PERSON> suggests, or try to rebuild the multiracial coalition that lifted <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to power in 1983 and made him the first mayor since the elder <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> to be re-elected. `` The reason <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> won _ and make no mistake about it _ is because he was able to graft liberal whites and Hispanics onto that huge bloc,'' said <PERSON> Clarence </PERSON> <PERSON> Page </PERSON>, a black who is a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION>'s editorial board. `` It does n't have to be tomorrow, but blacks should begin the process of looking for a candidate to do that. ... To suggest they sit on the sidelines and wait until the numbers grow enough to go it alone ... is just short-sighted.'' The city has roughly equal numbers of blacks and whites, but whites make up about 49 percent of the electorate, compared with about 43 percent for blacks. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Rose </PERSON>, a veteran political strategist who held top posts in the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> campaigns, said <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> won `` because a lot of white liberals and people who joined <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s reform movement were willing to give him a chance and because a lot of blacks did n't feel a sufficient amount of outrage and did n't vote.'' `` What <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> has to do now is make good on his campaign promises to be inclusive, racially and ethnically, in terms of appointments and contracts and promote reform-minded legislation,'' <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> said. `` If he does n't, the movement had better be ready.''
