<HEAD>August Space Shuttle Flight Delayed At Least Three Months</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf pvs, `Then will ...' to CORRECT from Atlantis
to Discovery.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two military space shuttle flights planned next summer will be delayed, one for at least three months, because work on the shuttle <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> is taking longer than expected. <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> said Friday the schedule had become too tight to support both missions and still preserve an October launch for the high-priority <ORGANIZATION> Galileo </ORGANIZATION> flight to <LOCATION> Jupiter </LOCATION>. A Discovery launch that had been scheduled for Aug. 10 will be delayed until at least November. <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>, which had a July 1 launch target, will be launched in early August, the space agency said. Both missions are to deploy classified <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> payloads. Unaffected will be Friday's planned liftoff of Atlantis with the Magellan-Venus spacecraft on board, the first planet-bound payload scheduled for release from a space shuttle. The schedule changes will have a ripple effect on launch dates later in the year, leaving <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> with six instead of its goal of seven shuttle launches this year. Officials have said the planned Oct. 12 liftoff of Atlantis with the Jupiter-orbiting <ORGANIZATION> Galileo </ORGANIZATION> spacecraft is a high-priority flight because there is only a 40-day launch period during which Jupiter and Earth are aligned properly. So it will be next in line after <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>'s August mission. Then will come the delayed Discovery military flight, probably in November, and a flight, probably in December, in which <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>'s crew is to deploy a communications satellite and retrieve a science satellite which has been orbiting since 1984. The mission of Discovery with the <ORGANIZATION> Hubble </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telescope </ORGANIZATION>, long awaited by astronomers, will slip from its present December launch slot into 1990. <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> said dates for missions after the <ORGANIZATION> Galileo </ORGANIZATION> flight will be determined later. `` <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> management has become increasingly concerned that the work involved in preparing the orbiter <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> for its first flight in over three years is taking long enough that it might endanger the option to launch <ORGANIZATION> Galileo </ORGANIZATION> at the opening of the launch window,'' said shuttle chief <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Truly </PERSON>. `` Our overriding objectives in this situation are to protect the <ORGANIZATION> Galileo </ORGANIZATION> window and to fly <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> as early as we can.'' Following the Challenger explosion in January 1986, the shuttle fleet was grounded for 32 months while the three remaining orbiters underwent major modifications to improve safety and performance. The modified Discovery has made two flights since the accident and <ORGANIZATION> Atlantis </ORGANIZATION> is about to make its second. Besides the Challenger-dictated changes, <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>, the first shuttle and a veteran of seven space trips, also had to undergo extensive alterations to its thermal protection tile system and is the last one to be returned to flight status. The <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> work is taking longer than planned because of a shortage of skilled engineers and technicians to process three shuttles simultaneously.
