<FIRST>r e AM-Opera     04-22 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Opera,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Met Serves Up Refreshing Elixir</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE SILVERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For those to whom a heavy diet of <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON>'s `` Ring Cycle'' is poison, the Metropolitan Opera has an antidote that's easy to swallow _ an `` Elixir of Love'' with superstars <PERSON> Luciano </PERSON> <PERSON> Pavarotti </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kathleen </PERSON> <PERSON> Battle </PERSON> <PERSON> Donizetti </PERSON>'s comic masterpiece _ which he dashed off in an amazing two weeks _ made its first appearance of the season Friday night to a standing-room-only crowd. It will be performed four more times during the final two weeks of the season, while most of the Met's attention is devoted to its new staging of <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON>'s four-part `` Der Ring Des Nibelungen.'' Luckily, this fading but still charming 1960 production by <PERSON> Nathaniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Merrill </PERSON> and <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Hearn </PERSON> practically runs by itself, like a windup clock. And with music so effervescent and a plot so foolproof, the audience is guaranteed a good time, even if the performance never quite sparkles as it should. <PERSON> Pavarotti </PERSON> started his career singing light tenor roles like <PERSON> Nemorino </PERSON>, the bumbling country bumpkin who tries to win the heart of his true love by drinking a magic potion. He's gone on to tackle heavier parts _ and lost some of his luster in the process _ but this role remains a favorite. Though he's always an agreeable performer, <PERSON> Pavarotti </PERSON> was not in top vocal form Friday night, straining for notes when he should have been caressing them. His big second-act aria, `` Una furtiva lagrima,'' drew the usual feverish ovation from his fans, but in truth it was only moderately soothing to the ear. Miss Battle, as the heroine <PERSON> Adina </PERSON>, took a while to warm up, at first sounding oddly detached as she has in other recent assignments at the Met. But after the intermission, she became more animated and produced a rich, full tone along with her famous silvery high notes. It was good to hear Doctor <PERSON> Dulcamara </PERSON>, the traveling quack who arrives in a balloon, sung with the firm, booming voice that bass <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Plishka </PERSON> displayed. Often the part is given to an aging singer who must rely on comic business to cover up an inability to get all the notes across. Less effective was <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> <PERSON> Nucci </PERSON> as Sergeant <PERSON> Belcore </PERSON>, <PERSON> Nemorino </PERSON>'s rival for the love of <PERSON> Adina </PERSON> His modest baritone just could n't hold its own in such high-powered vocal company. <PERSON> Marcello </PERSON> <PERSON> Panni </PERSON>, who conducted <PERSON> Pavarotti </PERSON> and Miss Battle in the same opera in Central Park last summer, was making his house debut and did n't quite have his act together. The orchestra sounded ragged at times, and the singers, especially <PERSON> Pavarotti </PERSON>, tended to go their own way where tempos were concerned.
