<HEAD>Soviet Military Aircraft to Carry Civilian Cargoes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Dozens of military aircraft will be diverted to civilian duty to haul 50,000 tons of farm produce, construction equipment, and other goods around the country this year, an official report said. The report Friday by the <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency gave no reason for the move. However, it said the military planes would be transporting southern fruit and vegetables to northern cities, including <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION>. Those cities suffer chronic shortages of such goods. Military aircraft have occasionally been used for civilian duty in the past. They helped deliver equipment and relief workers after the 1986 <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION> nuclear accident and the Armenian earthquake in December, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. A new resolution ordering the aircraft to carry civilian cargoes was adopted by the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministers </ORGANIZATION>, the news agency said. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said the 60 military transport planes in the program will include the <PERSON> Ruslan </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Antheus </LOCATION> jumbo jets, Il-76 turbojets and An-12 turboprops. It did not say when the program would begin or how long it would last. It said the jumbo jets `` are capable of bringing practically to any point in the country large structural elements, building and earth-moving machinery, cranes, excavators and transport vehicles.'' Col. Gen. <PERSON> Vyacheslav </PERSON> <PERSON> Yefanov </PERSON>, chief of the military transport division, was quoted by <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> as saying combat readiness will not be impaired. `` Crews will continue to upgrade their flying skills, improve maintenance of aircraft and will master radio communications,'' <PERSON> Yefanov </PERSON> said.
