<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Soviet deputy foreign minister arrived in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> on Saturday for talks aimed at overcoming problems facing the first Soviet-Chinese summit in 30 years, sources said. Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> is scheduled to come to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> on May 15. The two sides have had difficulty agreeing on a joint communique to be issued at the visit's end, said an Eastern European source, speaking on condition of anonymity. It is hoped the visit by Deputy Foreign Minister <PERSON> Igor </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogachev </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> will clear up these difficulties, specifically the Soviet and Chinese position on <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> and the war in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>. Other difficulties concern the vision that each nation has of future Sino-Soviet ties. <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> has played down the significance of its growing ties with <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, while the Soviets like to portray their improving rapport with the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> as a foreign relations coup. One indication of this occurred when the date of <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s visit was announced in February Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> ended a visit to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> on Feb. 3 by announcing the date. At a press conference that same day, a <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> official denied a date had been set. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> then waited two days to announce that the date was May 15. <PERSON> Rogachev </PERSON> arrived Saturday afternoon, a Chinese source said. His visit had been planned for some time but postponed for unknown reasons. Both <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> support a Vietnamese troop pullout from <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> by September. They also support an end to Chinese aid for <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>'s anti-Vietnamese guerrillas. <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> invaded <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> in late 1978 to replace the pro-Chinese <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> with a pro-Vietnamese puppet government. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> apparently still differ on the composition of a transitional government, which would rule until elections to replace the current Vietnamese-installed government. The last Soviet leader to visit <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> was <PERSON> Nikita </PERSON> <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON> in 1959.
