led a year ago will remain outside the party, according to a broadcast on <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> radio. It reported <PERSON> Mihaly </PERSON> <PERSON> Bihari </PERSON>, a political scientist and reform communist, said there were `` incompatible differences'' between the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and the four expelled last April. The three others, economist <PERSON> Laszlo </PERSON> <PERSON> Lengyel </PERSON>, historian <PERSON> Zoltan </PERSON> <PERSON> Biro </PERSON> and parliamentary deputy <PERSON> Zoltan </PERSON> <PERSON> Kiraly </PERSON>, announced earlier last week that they would not rejoin the party. The <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, the party's top disciplinary body, had reversed its expulsion order at a meeting Monday. <PERSON> Bihari </PERSON> was quoted by <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> radio as saying the party is paralyzed by irreconcilable differences within its own ranks. There has been discussion in recent weeks about a possible split between the party's reform and orthodox wings.
