<FIRST>r i AM-India-Dockworkers     04-22 0157</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Dockworkers,0192</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dockworkers Call off Strike After Agreement on Wages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s 125,000 dockworkers called off a 6-day-old strike Saturday after reaching an agreement with the government on higher wages, news reports said. The strike had paralyzed operations in the country's 10 major ports. Sailors from the Indian navy were deployed to unload essential goods. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> news agency quoted Transport Minister <PERSON> Rajesh </PERSON> <PERSON> Pilot </PERSON> as saying the five striking trade unions of stevedores, or dockworkers, had reached a wage settlement with the government. He said the workers would report for duty by Monday. The workers had been demanding a 25 percent hike in wages but the government offered only a 15 percent increase. An Indian dockhand earns between $ 90 and $ 180 per month. Pilot did not specify the increase agreed to in negotiations but said the five-year settlement would satisfy the workers' demands by the end of the contract.
