<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Solidarity     04-22 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Solidarity,0559</SECOND>
<HEAD>Solidarity Comes out of Trenches</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Solidarity activists are scouting for offices, hooking up telephones and signing up volunteer poll watchers in a flurry of activity after regaining legal status for their independent labor movement. Near the center of <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>, a former history institute is being transformed into the <ORGANIZATION> Solidarity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>'s national election headquarters. At another location, a small union press office has opened. At a third spot, opposition editors are planning to put out a newspaper. Solidarity volunteers _ university students, mothers on leave from jobs, longtime activists and others _ are struggling with typical Polish shortages of office supplies, furniture and phone lines. But they no longer need look over their shoulders. The government crushed Solidarity, the first independent union in the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc, during a martial law crackdown in 1981 and later banned it. After years of illegal activity, Solidarity recaptured its legal status when a government-controlled court lifted the ban Monday. The legalization stemmed from talks between the opposition and the government that concluded in an agreement April 5. The government also agreed to free elections to a new chamber of parliament and other electoral reforms in exchange for political and economic cooperation from Solidarity. Before it was suppressed, Solidarity claimed 10 million members. However, speaking at the end of a three-day visit to <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, Solidarity leader <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> predicted Saturday in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> that his labor movement will dwindle as it gives rise to splinter groups during the reforms in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. `` From Solidarity, other economic and political organizations will be born,'' said <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>. `` Solidarity for the moment is huge, but it will become smaller with the growth of other organizations. This is the logical course of events.'' The first major office to open in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> since legalization was the <ORGANIZATION> Solidarity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> headquarters in an empty former history institute on the edge of the picturesque Saxon Garden park. The organization, technically separate from Solidarity, is racing against early deadlines for finding candidates. It is collecting nominating signatures, running campaigns, and training election observers for parliamentary voting scheduled for June 4 and June 18. On Friday, <PERSON> Jacek </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuron </PERSON>, a veteran activist slated to run for the existing upper chamber of parliament, scrambled through the building holding quick chats with several prominent activists in the bustling center. `` It's full of problems,'' he replied when asked about the practical side of ushering in legal activity. `` We do n't have telephones, we do n't have space, we do n't have anything _ but we will.'' <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Litynski </PERSON>, spokesman for the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> regional chapter of Solidarity, said: `` The mood is getting hotter and hotter because of the elections.'' <PERSON> Anatol </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawina </PERSON>, a Solidarity representative to the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, said he hopes to line up 100,000 people nationwide to help guard against cheating at the 22,000 polling sites. Elsewhere in the country, local election offices and news bureaus were also being opened. The Election Newspaper, a newspaper that expects to circulate 500,000 copies, has found offices in an empty building in central <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> Skalski </PERSON>, one of the editors. The paper will become the first opposition mass-circulation daily in the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc with its first edition, scheduled for May.
</TEXT>
