<HEAD>Prime Minister Condemns Extremists in Police</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prime Minister <PERSON> Anibal </PERSON> <PERSON> Cavaco </PERSON> <PERSON> Silva </PERSON> on Saturday blamed extreme leftists for prompting demands by police officers to form a union, news reports said. The demands provoked violent clashes within the police force. Six policemen were arrested in the clashes Friday between riot police and fellow officers demanding union rights. They were released Saturday pending trial. About 100 uniformed officers greeted the release with victory signs and calls for further protest. Riot police used water cannons, dogs and batons Friday against protesting officers outside the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>. As the riot escalated, civilians joined demonstrators in hurling stones at the riot squad. Seventeen people were reported injured. `` Extremist forces, communist forces and some socialists were behind the movements in the <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Silva </PERSON> was quoted by the national <ORGANIZATION> Lusa </ORGANIZATION> news agency as saying. <PERSON> Cavaco </PERSON> <PERSON> Silva </PERSON>'s center-right Social Democratic government has not granted union rights to uniformed police units, saying their militarized status makes trade unions unconstitutional. <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION>'s two major trade union federations, the Communist-inspired General Confederation of Portuguese Workers and the Socialist-led <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, called for a demonstration Monday to protest the actions of the riot police. General Workers Union General Secretary <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Torres </PERSON> <PERSON> Couto </PERSON>, also a Socialist deputy in the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>, said he would ask for a parliamentary inquiry into Friday's riot and demanded the resignation of Internal Affairs Minister <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> da </PERSON> <PERSON> Silveira </PERSON> <PERSON> Godinho </PERSON>.
