<FIRST>r a AM-LouisianaSpill     04-22 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Louisiana Spill,0531</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cleanup of Waste Water Continues From Louisiana Spill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAYOU SORREL, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Four pumps were used to empty the remaining oil-tainted water from a disabled, leaking barge Saturday and workers laid out absorbent pads to clean up the impurities that spilled into <LOCATION> Grand </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. Officials said 10,000 gallons of the non-hazardous waste material _ water with small percentages of oil and alcohol _ spilled into the river early Friday on a loading dock on the river about 35 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Baton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rouge </LOCATION>. Earlier estimates had put the amount of the spill at 100,000 gallons or more. `` As of 10 a.m., they were pumping out the barge into vacuum trucks,'' said <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Wootten </PERSON>, a marine science technician for the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION>. `` They were one behind another. As soon as one is filled, another pulls up.'' The spill occurred when a barge carrying 900,000 gallons of the waste water from an Exxon plant in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> buckled in the middle while workers unloaded the waste into tanker trucks. There were initial fears for the fragile environment _ the site of the spill is near a large marshland area _ and some fish died. But authorities said the spill was quickly contained by booms and the environmental damage would be minimal. `` They have booms in place and only a small amount of the product went down river. It is being retrieved,'' <PERSON> Wootten </PERSON> said. Absorbent pads have been put out to soak up the impurities in the river, officials said. <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Vice </PERSON>, an employee at <ORGANIZATION> GSX </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Land </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treatment </ORGANIZATION>, which was being paid to dispose of the waste water, did not have the required <ORGANIZATION> Merchant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> certification for performing the work at the time of the accident, said <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> Chief Warrant Officer <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Doss </PERSON>. GSX is assuming responsibility for the cleanup, officials said. GSX spokesman <PERSON> Bobby </PERSON> <PERSON> Mayweather </PERSON> said Saturday afternoon that Vice was at the site and unavailable for comment. A woman answering the telephone at Vice's home in White Castle also said he was unavailable. <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>, which has been harshly criticized in the past month because of the 10 million-gallon spill from an oil tanker that hit a reef off <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, had no involvement in Friday's spill except that one of its plants was the source of the waste water, officials said. `` Exxon is getting a bad rap on this,'' <PERSON> Wootten </PERSON> said. `` They had nothing to do with the spill. They had just hired a company to haul the product off. In fact, <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> should be commended _ they have no liability and they still sent a clean-up crew.'' <PERSON> Wootten </PERSON> said the amount of the so-called `` slop water'' leaking from the barge into the <LOCATION> Grand </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> was very small. `` Drip, drip, drip, that's all it is,'' he said. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Dubois </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Palmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, owner of the barge, said the water-alcohol mixture is used to wash out tanks and ships. When it's dirty with oil residue, it becomes waste water, he said. Exxon estimated the water contained 3 percent oil and 7 percent alcohol. The alcohol began evaporating after the spill.
</TEXT>
