<FIRST>r a AM-AIDSStudy     04-22 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS Study,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pilot AIDS Study A Success, Officials Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 People responded with surprising frankness to questions about sexual habits and drug use in a pilot study to determine the prevalence of AIDS, suggesting a similar study could succeed nationwide, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> health officials say. Of the 308 eligible residents approached in January and February at their homes in <LOCATION> Allegheny </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, 263 _ or 85 percent _ agreed to fill out a form containing questions about sexual habits and drug use and to give a blood sample for the study, in exchange for $ 50. `` I'd call it a surprising success,'' said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Hurley </PERSON>, project officer for the Atlanta-based <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION>, which commissioned the survey. The results were discussed Friday at a meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> Allegheny </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, which approved the pilot study last fall. Still unanswered, researchers said, is whether people participating in a survey are actually telling the truth about their intimate habits, and whether a national survey could be done at close to the original estimated cost of $ 25 million. Besides the <LOCATION> Allegheny </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> study, a pilot survey is slated to start this summer in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>. One in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, was scrapped in August after community leaders complained it appeared to single out blacks. The pilot studies are running about 20 percent over budget, largely because of the effort required to quell community concern about them, <PERSON> Hurley </PERSON> said. In <LOCATION> Allegheny </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, out of an original pool of 450 homes randomly chosen for the survey, interviewers found 308 where a person at home was aged between 18 and 54, the survey's target ages. In all, 263 of the 308 people agreed to fill out a form and give blood. Most residents said they agreed to take part because they wanted to help research into acquired immune deficiency syndrome. Only 15 said the main reason was to get the $ 50 paid to everyone who answered the 22 questions and gave a blood sample. AIDS tests were run on all of the blood samples, but county health officials said they will not release the results. Even survey participants were not given the results of their own blood tests, but those worried about having been exposed to AIDS were advised to contact their doctor or a health clinic.
</TEXT>
