<FIRST>u i AM-France-Missile     04-22 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-Missile,0424</SECOND>
<HEAD>Irish Militiamen, U.S. Businessman Arrested in Arms Delivery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three Protestant militiamen from <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> and an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> businessman were arrested in the delivery of missile-launcher parts to a South African diplomat, a government official said Saturday. The French official said the three militiamen belong to the <ORGANIZATION> Ulster </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, the largest paramilitary organization in <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>. The arrests were made Friday at a <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> hotel four men were delivering spare parts for the British-made Blowpipe shoulder-carried missile launcher to <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Storm </PERSON>, a South African diplomat, the official said, speaking on condition of anonymity. He said Storm, who is covered by diplomatic immunity, was released but the other four were held for questioning at the offices of the <ORGANIZATION> DST </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s counterespionage agency. There was no official announcement of the arrests. News reports identified the three militiamen as <PERSON> Noel </PERSON> <PERSON> Little </PERSON>, 40; <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Quinn </PERSON>, 41; and <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>, 50. The news agency Agence France-Presse identified the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> as 40-year-old <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Bernhart </PERSON>. The agency said without providing details that <PERSON> Bernhart </PERSON> kept an office in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>. However, his name was not listed in the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> phone book or a local register of companies. French law permits police to hold suspects for questioning for up to four days before they are charged with an offense. A duty officer at the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>, which is responsible for the counterespionage agency, said he could not comment on the report. In <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> department </ORGANIZATION> confirmed Saturday that Storm was on the staff of the South African embassy in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> and said there would be an investigation of the case. The <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> newspaper <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Monde </PERSON> said it appeared the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africans </LOCATION> hoped to copy the delivered parts to produce a similar anti-aircraft missile of their own, possibly for export. It said the spare parts apparently had been stolen but gave no details. None of the reports carried details of payments for the parts. In <LOCATION> Belfast </LOCATION>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ulster </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Constablulary </ORGANIZATION>, speaking on condition of anonymity, said a dummy Blowpipe missile was stolen over the weekend of April 8-9 from a <ORGANIZATION> Territorial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, or national guard, base in <LOCATION> Newtonards </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Down </LOCATION>. He said the security forces insist it had no working parts. There was no known evidence of a link between the discovery and the arrests in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. The Blowpipe, sometimes compared to the U.S.-made Stinger missile launcher, weighs about 45 pounds and fires 76mm guided surface-to-air missiles.
