<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Howard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> officials announced Saturday that <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cheek </PERSON>, who has been president of the predominantly black institution for 20 years, will retire in June. Cheek, 56, began at <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> in 1969, and his resignation is to take effect June 30. The <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> quoted sources in Sunday's editions as saying Cheek is expected to be nominated by President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to become ambassador to the Republic of <LOCATION> Cameroon </LOCATION>. During his tenure, he was confronted with a number of student protests similar to the one earlier this year when a three-day takeover of the university administration building forced the resignation of <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Atwater </PERSON> from the university's board of trustees. Last week, students staged a rally on campus and held a candlelight vigil outside Cheek's home, charging the university had n't complied with a March 9 agreement that ended the anti-Atwater protests. Students also complained that financial aid and campus security problems have yet to be resolved.
