<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The first half of fiscal 1989 ended with a budget deficit that is running 7.4 percent ahead of last year's, according to the government's latest report on its financial situation. For the first six months of the 1989 fiscal year, which began Oct. 1, the budget deficit totaled $ 128.43 billion, up from the $ 119.61 billion shortfall posted in the first six months of last year, the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Friday. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration is estimating this year's deficit will total $ 163.3 billion, up 5.3 percent from the $ 155.1 billion shortfall posted in for all of fiscal 1988. Under the Gramm-Rudman deficit-reduction law, this year's deficit was not supposed to exceed $ 146 billion. The administration and congressional leaders last week unveiled a compromise plan designed to reduce the deficit in the next fiscal year to $ 99.4 billion, just within the $ 100 billion target for fiscal 1990 established under Gramm-Rudman.
