<HEAD>Warren Buffett's Annual Meeting: Exalted Wizard Holds Court</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Annual Meeting Season</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Many company bosses duck investor salvos at annual meetings, but <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> <PERSON> Buffett </PERSON> likely will bask in shareholder adulation because he's enriched them for the 24th year. <PERSON> Buffett </PERSON>, one of the world's wealthiest people, is chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Berkshire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hathaway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a $ 6 billion conglomerate with interests that include an encyclopedia, a homespun candy maker, an <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION> furniture mart, a giant insurance company and investments in <ORGANIZATION> Coca </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Salomon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, among others. Folksy, charming and unconventional, the 57-year-old investor wows shareholders and stock analysts with a pithy annual report he writes himself, filled with insights into what he considers good and bad in his business and the economy in general. It's earned him the nickname, `` Oracle of <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION>.'' This year, <PERSON> Buffett </PERSON> began the report with a 21-page letter to shareholders, telling them the stock market is lousy, corporate taxes are higher and the takeover business is getting expensive. Nonetheless, he wrote, <ORGANIZATION> Berkshire </ORGANIZATION>'s management team gained $ 569 million in net worth for them in 1988, contributing to an average net worth gain of 23 percent over the last 24 years. He also proclaimed <ORGANIZATION> Berkshire </ORGANIZATION> had made a great investment in <ORGANIZATION> Borsheim </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION>, a flourishing <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION> jewelry business. `` We continue to concentrate our investments in a very few companies that we try to understand well,'' <PERSON> Buffett </PERSON> wrote. `` There are only a handful of businesses about which we have strong long-term convictions. Therefore, when we find such a business, we want to participate in a meaningful way. We agree with Mae West: ` Too much of a good thing can be wonderful.''' <PERSON> Buffett </PERSON>'s report is a prelude to <ORGANIZATION> Berkshire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hathaway </ORGANIZATION>'s annual meeting, which he's holding Monday in <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION>, the company's headquarters He plans to make shareholders feel like they're at a family reunion. `` After the meeting we will have several buses available to take you to visit Mrs. B at the <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> Furniture Mart and <PERSON> Ike </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON> at <ORGANIZATION> Borsheim </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Buffett </PERSON> wrote to the shareholders. `` Be prepared for bargains.'' The biggest bargain <ORGANIZATION> Berkshire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hathaway </ORGANIZATION> shareholders ever got was buying the company's stock, which had a book value of about $ 20 a share in the mid 1960s, when <PERSON> Buffett </PERSON> acquired what was then <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> cloth milling concern with $ 10 million in assets. Now its book value is nearly $ 3,000 a share and it trades on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> at nearly $ 5,900 a share. <PERSON> Berkshire </PERSON> <PERSON> Hathaway </PERSON> is considered such a gem that takeover strategist <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boone </PERSON> <PERSON> Pickens </PERSON> ranked it last month as among the top 20 of 1,000 big companies for what he called its commitment to shareholders. <PERSON> Buffett </PERSON>'s annual report is so widely followed that <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Today </ORGANIZATION> said recently it `` runs a good chance of being the only one anyone actually reads on or off Wall Street.'' <PERSON> Verne </PERSON> <PERSON> McKenzie </PERSON>, <PERSON> Berkshire </PERSON> <PERSON> Hathaway </PERSON>'s chief financial officer, said the company is besieged with requests for the annual report and shareholders flock like pilgrims to the annual meeting. `` People travel here from the far reaches of the country and the world,'' he said. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Corporate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Annual </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reports </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a professional annual report publishing concern, gave high marks to <PERSON> Buffett </PERSON>'s yearly prognostications to shareholders, largely because it showed he was honest and direct with fellow owners of the company. `` <PERSON> Buffett </PERSON> is one of the four or five richest men in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> said. `` When he speaks, people listen. He uses his report to say what he wants to say. He uses the report to underscore his own investment principles and the keys to his success.'' Nonetheless, <PERSON> Buffett </PERSON> is not universally admired. <PERSON> Sid </PERSON> <PERSON> Cato </PERSON>, publisher of a monthly newsletter on annual reports based in <LOCATION> Waukesha </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, ranked <ORGANIZATION> Berkshire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hathaway </ORGANIZATION>'s as one of the 10 worst last year, largely because of what he called <PERSON> Buffett </PERSON>'s inflated ego. `` I wrote, ` Mr. <PERSON> Buffett </PERSON>, you're starting to get on my nerves already, enough already,'' <PERSON> Cato </PERSON> said. Asked if he'd seen this year's annual report, <PERSON> Cato </PERSON> said, `` No, he has not seen fit to send me a copy.''
